<Link id="l00202" /><CodeLine lineNumber="202"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The location of the rebase info inside the binary is described by</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00203" /><CodeLine lineNumber="203"><Highlight kind="comment">/// LC&#95;DYLD&#95;INFO load command. Dyld rebases an image whenever dyld loads it at</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00204" /><CodeLine lineNumber="204"><Highlight kind="comment">/// an address different from its preferred address.  The rebase information is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00205" /><CodeLine lineNumber="205"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a stream of byte sized opcodes whose symbolic names start with</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00206" /><CodeLine lineNumber="206"><Highlight kind="comment">/// REBASE&#95;OPCODE&#95;. Conceptually the rebase information is a table of tuples:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00207" /><CodeLine lineNumber="207"><Highlight kind="comment">///   &lt;seg-index, seg-offset, type&gt;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00208" /><CodeLine lineNumber="208"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The opcodes are a compressed way to encode the table by only</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00209" /><CodeLine lineNumber="209"><Highlight kind="comment">/// encoding when a column changes.  In addition simple patterns</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00210" /><CodeLine lineNumber="210"><Highlight kind="comment">/// like &quot;every n&#39;th offset for m times&quot; can be encoded in a few</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00211" /><CodeLine lineNumber="211"><Highlight kind="comment">/// bytes.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00218" /><CodeLine lineNumber="218"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The location of the bind info inside the binary is described by</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00219" /><CodeLine lineNumber="219"><Highlight kind="comment">/// LC&#95;DYLD&#95;INFO load command. Dyld binds an image during the loading process,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00220" /><CodeLine lineNumber="220"><Highlight kind="comment">/// if the image requires any pointers to be initialized to symbols in other</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00223" /><CodeLine lineNumber="223"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a table of tuples: &lt;seg-index, seg-offset, type, symbol-library-ordinal,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00224" /><CodeLine lineNumber="224"><Highlight kind="comment">/// symbol-name, addend&gt; The opcodes are a compressed way to encode the table by</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00225" /><CodeLine lineNumber="225"><Highlight kind="comment">/// only encoding when a column changes.  In addition simple patterns like for</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00226" /><CodeLine lineNumber="226"><Highlight kind="comment">/// runs of pointers initialized to the same value can be encoded in a few</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00227" /><CodeLine lineNumber="227"><Highlight kind="comment">/// bytes.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00234" /><CodeLine lineNumber="234"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The location of the weak bind info inside the binary is described by</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00235" /><CodeLine lineNumber="235"><Highlight kind="comment">/// LC&#95;DYLD&#95;INFO load command. Some C++ programs require dyld to unique symbols</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00236" /><CodeLine lineNumber="236"><Highlight kind="comment">/// so that all images in the process use the same copy of some code/data. This</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00237" /><CodeLine lineNumber="237"><Highlight kind="comment">/// step is done after binding. The content of the weak&#95;bind info is an opcode</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00238" /><CodeLine lineNumber="238"><Highlight kind="comment">/// stream like the bind&#95;info.  But it is sorted alphabetically by symbol name.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00239" /><CodeLine lineNumber="239"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This enable dyld to walk all images with weak binding information in order</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00240" /><CodeLine lineNumber="240"><Highlight kind="comment">/// and look for collisions.  If there are no collisions, dyld does no updating.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00241" /><CodeLine lineNumber="241"><Highlight kind="comment">/// That means that some fixups are also encoded in the bind&#95;info.  For</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00242" /><CodeLine lineNumber="242"><Highlight kind="comment">/// instance, all calls to &quot;operator new&quot; are first bound to libstdc++.dylib</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00243" /><CodeLine lineNumber="243"><Highlight kind="comment">/// using the information in bind&#95;info.  Then if some image overrides operator</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00244" /><CodeLine lineNumber="244"><Highlight kind="comment">/// new that is detected when the weak&#95;bind information is processed and the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00245" /><CodeLine lineNumber="245"><Highlight kind="comment">/// call to operator new is then rebound.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00246" /><CodeLine lineNumber="246" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/macho/weakbindinfo"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">struct </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/macho/weakbindinfo">WeakBindInfo</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00248" /><CodeLine lineNumber="248"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// but the proper support will be added later.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00249" /><CodeLine lineNumber="249" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/macho/weakbindinfo/#aea259cd75b7493da0eb265b966f0bc41"><Highlight kind="normal">  <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/arrayref">ArrayRef&lt;uint8&#95;t&gt;</a> <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/macho/weakbindinfo/#aea259cd75b7493da0eb265b966f0bc41">Opcodes</a>;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00251" /><CodeLine lineNumber="251"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00252" /><CodeLine lineNumber="252"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The location of the lazy bind info inside the binary is described by</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00253" /><CodeLine lineNumber="253"><Highlight kind="comment">/// LC&#95;DYLD&#95;INFO load command. Some uses of external symbols do not need to be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00254" /><CodeLine lineNumber="254"><Highlight kind="comment">/// bound immediately. Instead they can be lazily bound on first use.  The</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00255" /><CodeLine lineNumber="255"><Highlight kind="comment">/// lazy&#95;bind contains a stream of BIND opcodes to bind all lazy symbols. Normal</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00256" /><CodeLine lineNumber="256"><Highlight kind="comment">/// use is that dyld ignores the lazy&#95;bind section when loading an image.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00257" /><CodeLine lineNumber="257"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Instead the static linker arranged for the lazy pointer to initially point</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00258" /><CodeLine lineNumber="258"><Highlight kind="comment">/// to a helper function which pushes the offset into the lazy&#95;bind area for the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00259" /><CodeLine lineNumber="259"><Highlight kind="comment">/// symbol needing to be bound, then jumps to dyld which simply adds the offset</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00260" /><CodeLine lineNumber="260"><Highlight kind="comment">/// to lazy&#95;bind&#95;off to get the information on what to bind.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00261" /><CodeLine lineNumber="261" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/macho/lazybindinfo"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">struct </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/macho/lazybindinfo">LazyBindInfo</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00262" /><CodeLine lineNumber="262" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/macho/lazybindinfo/#a2d32b13b4857e04203d0307f0faa3af5"><Highlight kind="normal">  <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/arrayref">ArrayRef&lt;uint8&#95;t&gt;</a> <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/macho/lazybindinfo/#a2d32b13b4857e04203d0307f0faa3af5">Opcodes</a>;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00263" /><CodeLine lineNumber="263"><Highlight kind="normal">&#125;;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00264" /><CodeLine lineNumber="264"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00265" /><CodeLine lineNumber="265"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The location of the export info inside the binary is described by</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00266" /><CodeLine lineNumber="266"><Highlight kind="comment">/// LC&#95;DYLD&#95;INFO load command. The symbols exported by a dylib are encoded in a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00267" /><CodeLine lineNumber="267"><Highlight kind="comment">/// trie.  This is a compact representation that factors out common prefixes. It</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00268" /><CodeLine lineNumber="268"><Highlight kind="comment">/// also reduces LINKEDIT pages in RAM because it encodes all information (name,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00269" /><CodeLine lineNumber="269"><Highlight kind="comment">/// address, flags) in one small, contiguous range. The export area is a stream</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00270" /><CodeLine lineNumber="270"><Highlight kind="comment">/// of nodes.  The first node sequentially is the start node for the trie. Nodes</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00271" /><CodeLine lineNumber="271"><Highlight kind="comment">/// for a symbol start with a uleb128 that is the length of the exported symbol</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00272" /><CodeLine lineNumber="272"><Highlight kind="comment">/// information for the string so far. If there is no exported symbol, the node</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00273" /><CodeLine lineNumber="273"><Highlight kind="comment">/// starts with a zero byte. If there is exported info, it follows the length.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00274" /><CodeLine lineNumber="274"><Highlight kind="comment">/// First is a uleb128 containing flags. Normally, it is followed by</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00275" /><CodeLine lineNumber="275"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a uleb128 encoded offset which is location of the content named</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00276" /><CodeLine lineNumber="276"><Highlight kind="comment">/// by the symbol from the mach&#95;header for the image.  If the flags</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00277" /><CodeLine lineNumber="277"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is EXPORT&#95;SYMBOL&#95;FLAGS&#95;REEXPORT, then following the flags is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00278" /><CodeLine lineNumber="278"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a uleb128 encoded library ordinal, then a zero terminated</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00279" /><CodeLine lineNumber="279"><Highlight kind="comment">/// UTF8 string.  If the string is zero length, then the symbol</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00280" /><CodeLine lineNumber="280"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is re-export from the specified dylib with the same name.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00281" /><CodeLine lineNumber="281"><Highlight kind="comment">/// If the flags is EXPORT&#95;SYMBOL&#95;FLAGS&#95;STUB&#95;AND&#95;RESOLVER, then following</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00282" /><CodeLine lineNumber="282"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the flags is two uleb128s: the stub offset and the resolver offset.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00283" /><CodeLine lineNumber="283"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The stub is used by non-lazy pointers.  The resolver is used</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00284" /><CodeLine lineNumber="284"><Highlight kind="comment">/// by lazy pointers and must be called to get the actual address to use.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00285" /><CodeLine lineNumber="285"><Highlight kind="comment">/// After the optional exported symbol information is a byte of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00286" /><CodeLine lineNumber="286"><Highlight kind="comment">/// how many edges (0-255) that this node has leaving it,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00287" /><CodeLine lineNumber="287"><Highlight kind="comment">/// followed by each edge.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00288" /><CodeLine lineNumber="288"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Each edge is a zero terminated UTF8 of the addition chars</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00289" /><CodeLine lineNumber="289"><Highlight kind="comment">/// in the symbol, followed by a uleb128 offset for the node that</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00290" /><CodeLine lineNumber="290"><Highlight kind="comment">/// edge points to.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00291" /><CodeLine lineNumber="291" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/macho/exportinfo"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">struct </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/macho/exportinfo">ExportInfo</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
